Question: What is the relation between an edge location and a region or AZ?
Id: 478
Answer: They are unrelated. There are more edge locations than regions, and they are located at difference places.

Question: What is a CloudFront origin?
Id: 479
Answer: The original location of delivered content.

Question: What are possible CloudFront origins within AWS?
Id: 480
Answer: S3 bucket, EC2 instance, Elastic Load Balancer, Route53.

Question: Does CloudFront support third-party origins (non-AWS origins)?
Id: 481
Answer: Yes.

Question: What is a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 482
Answer: The name given to a CDN, wich consists of a collection of Edge Locations.

Question: Can CloudFront deliver dynamic, interactive, and streaming websites?
Id: 483
Answer: Yes.

Question: Name two types of CloudFront distributions?
Id: 484
Answer: Web distribution and RTMP distribution.

Question: What does RTMP stand for?
Id: 485
Answer: Real Time Messaging Protocol.

Question: When would you use a CloudFront RTMP distribution.
Id: 486
Answer: For media streaming using Adobe Flash.

Question: Are CloudFront edge locations read-only?
Id: 487
Answer: No, you can also PUT or POST to edge locations.

Question: How long does CloudFront cache content at an edge location?
Id: 488
Answer: For the configured Time To Live (TTL).

Question: Can you manually clear an object from a CloudFront edge location cache?
Id: 489
Answer: Yes, you can, but you will be charged for it.

Question: Why would you manually clear an object from a CloudFront edge location cache?
Id: 490
Answer: To make sure that end-users see the most recent version of the object.

SubTopic: Create a CloudFront CDN
Id: 491

Lab: Create a CloudFront CDN
Id: 492
Step: Log into the AWS console.
Step: Create an S3 bucket in a very remote region (e.g. Syndney).
Step: Upload a very large image into the remote bucket. Make it publicly readable.
Step: Open the image (using force refresh on the browser). Observe it takes a long time to download.
Step: Initiate creation of a CloudFront distribution:
Step: ... Choose the S3 bucket as the origin.
Step: ... Enable Restrict Bucket Access.
Step: ... Create a new origin access identity.
Step: ... Update the bucket policy to grant read access.
Step: ... Redirect HTTP to HTTPS.
Step: Monitor the distribution to observe when the Status reaches Deployed.
Step: Observe that retrieving the image through S3 still is slow (remember to force the browser to hard refresh)
Step: Construct the URL to retrieve the image using the CDN
Step: Retrieve the image using the CDN. Observe that the first retrieval is still slow.
Step: Retrieve the image using the CDN again. Observe that the first retrieval is fast, even if you force a hard refresh.
Step: Remove read access for all users for the image in the bucket.
Step: Observe that retrieving the image using the URL for the S3 bucket returns an error.
Step: Observe that retrieving the image using the URL for the CloudFront distribution succeeds.
Step: Observe that retrieving the image using the URL for the CloudFront redirects HTTP to HTTPS.
Step: Clean up.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for static web content (e.g. HTML, CSS, client-side JavaScript, graphics)?
Id: 493
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for dynamic web content (e.g. PHP)?
Id: 494
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for distributing media files using HTTP or HTTPS?
Id: 495
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for adding, updating, or deleting objects (PUT, POST, PATCH, DELETE, ...)?
Id: 496
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for posting web forms?
Id: 497
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for live streams?
Id: 498
Answer: Web distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for RTMP content?
Id: 499
Answer: RTMP distribution.

Question: What type of CloudFront distribution would you use for Adobe Flash content?
Id: 500
Answer: RTMP distribution.

Question: What is the "Origin Domain Name" for a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 501
Answer: An AWS resource name (S3 bucket, EC2 instance, Elastic Load Balancer, Route53) or non-AWS domain name.

Question: What is the "Origin Path" for a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 502
Answer: CloudFront appends this to the Origin Domain Name when forwarding the request to the origin server. Typically the name of a folder in an S3 bucket.

Question: Should you include slashes (/) in "Origin Path" for a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 503
Answer: Include the leading slash but not the trailing slash.

Question: What is the "Origin ID" for a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 504
Answer: A descriptive name for the origin within the distribution.

Question: What is "Restrict Bucket Access" for a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 505
Answer: Is set to "Yes, restrict" it forces users to get the content through CloudFront and they cannot get it directly from the S3 bucket.

Question: "Restrict Bucket Access" in CloudFront is typically used in combination with what other feature?
Id: 506
Answer: URL signing and cookie signing.

Question: "Restrict Bucket Access" in CloudFront requires what security feature?
Id: 507
Answer: An origin access identity with the proper permissions to access the origin.

Question: What is the most common mistake with enabling "Restrict Bucket Access"?
Id: 508
Answer: Forget setting "Yes, Update Bucket Policy" for "Grant Read Permissions on Bucket".

Question: What is "Path Pattern" in a CloudFront distribution behavior?
Id: 509
Answer: Matches on a file pattern (e.g. only jpeg extensions) to route a request to particular origin.

Question: What are the possible values for "Viewer Protocol Policy" in a CloudFront distribution behavior?
Id: 510
Answer: HTTP and HTTPS, Redirect HTTP to HTTPS, HTTPS Only.

Question: What do you need to do if you want to allow users to upload content?
Id: 511
Answer: Include PUT, POST, PATCH, DELETE in "Allowed HTTP Methods" in a CloudFront distribution behavior.

Question: Name 2 options for controlling the TTL of cached objects.
Id: 512
Answer: Using the cache headers provided by the origin server, or customized values specified in the CloudFront configuration.

Question: What is the advantage of using a long TTL in CloudFront?
Id: 513
Answer: Better cache hit rate (fewer requests to the origin server).

Question: What is the disadvantage of using a long TTL in CloudFront?
Id: 514
Answer: It takes longer for end-users to see an updated version of the content.

Question: What is an alternative to flushing the cache when you want users to see a new version of content?
Id: 515
Answer: Encode a version into the content name (into the URL).

Question: What is "Restrict Viewer Access" in a CloudFront distribution behavior?
Id: 516
Answer: It enables URL signing and Cookie signing.

Question: What is "Restrict Viewer Access" typically used for in CloudFront?
Id: 517
Answer: To make sure that only authorized (paying) customers can access content.

Question: How would you make sure that only authorized (paying) customers can access content?
Id: 518
Answer: Enable "Restrict Viewer Access" in CloudFront to enable URL signing and cookie signing.

Question: What is "Price Class" in a CloudFront distribution distribution settings?
Id: 519
Answer: Determines the set of edge locations that will cache the content (US, Canada, Europe only, or also Asia, or all locations).

Question: What does WAF stand for?
Id: 520
Answer: Web Application Firewall.

Question: What is WAF used for in CloudFront?
Id: 521
Answer: To prevent application-layer attachs on the web server.

Question: What does the default URL for a CloudFront distribution look like?
Id: 522
Answer: xxx.cloudfront.net where xxx is a random string.

Question: What is "Alternate Domain Names" in a CloudFront distribution distribution settings?
Id: 523
Answer: Allows you to use your own domain name instead of the default CloudFront domain name.

Question: How does using your own domain name affect HTTPS?
Id: 524
Answer: You must provide your own certificate and store it in Amazon Certificate Manager (ACM).

Question: Does CloudFront support HTTP2?
Id: 525
Answer: Yes, it is enabled by default but it can be disabled.

Question: Does CloudFront support IPv6?
Id: 526
Answer: Yes, it is enabled by default but it can be disabled.

Question: How long does it take to create or delete a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 527
Answer: A long time, up to 15 minutes.

Question: Why does it take so long to create or delete a CloudFront distribution?
Id: 528
Answer: Because many edge locations need to be updated.

Question: How is the distribution domain name related to the distribution ID?
Id: 529
Answer: They are unrelated. They both contain random strings, but they are different random strings.

Question: Is it possible to have multiple origin servers for a single CloudFront distribution?
Id: 530
Answer: Yes.

Question: Is it possible to have multiple behaviors for a single CloudFront distribution?
Id: 531
Answer: Yes.

Question: What would you do if you want your CloudFront content only to be available in certain countries?
Id: 532
Answer: Enable Geo Restrictions.

Question: What are the two methods for configuring Geo Restrictions?
Id: 533
Answer: Either a white list or a black list of countries (but not both).

Question: What is a CloudFront invalidation?
Id: 534
Answer: A request to remove cached objects from edge locations.

Question: How would you remove CloudFront cached objects from edge locations?
Id: 535
Answer: Create an invalidation. Note there is a charge.

Question: What would you do if you create an updated version of content, and you want all users to see the new content immediately?
Id: 536
Answer: Create a CloudFront invalidation to flush cached content from the edge locations. Note there is a charge.

Question: What would you do if you accidentally put some confidential information on the web, and you want to remove it immediately?
Id: 537
Answer: Create a CloudFront invalidation to flush cached content from the edge locations. Note there is a charge.

SubTopic: S3 Security and Encryption
Id: 538

Question: What are the default permissions for an S3 bucket?
Id: 539
Answer: Private: only the owner (the creator) has full access, and everyone else has no access.

Question: Name 2 mechanisms for securing S3 buckets:
Id: 540
Answer: Bucket policies and Access Control Lists (ACLs).

Question: Name 1 mechanism for securing S3 buckets.
Id: 541
Answer: Access Control Lists (ACLs).

Question: What can Policies be attached to directly in S3?
Id: 542
Answer: Only buckets.

Question: What can Access Control Lists be attached to in S3?
Id: 543
Answer: Both buckets and objects.

Question: Whose access can be controlled by an S3 ACL?
Id: 544
Answer: The owner account, other accounts, public access, and (for buckets) the S3 log delivery group.

Question: Name 5 permissions that can be granted in S3 bucket ACL.
Id: 545
Answer: (1) List objects (2) Create or overwrite or delete object (3) Read bucket ACL (4) Write bucket ACL (5) Full access

Question: Name 4 permissions that can be granted in S3 object ACL.
Id: 546
Answer: (1) Read object data and metada (2) Read object ACL (3) Write object ACL (4) Full access

Question: Where is the permission to write to an object controlled?
Id: 547
Answer: In the ACL of the bucket (not the ACL of the object).

Question: What does ACL stand for?
Id: 548
Answer: Access Control List.

Question: Describe S3 logging.
Id: 549
Answer: If Server Access Logging is enabled on a bucket, all requests for the bucket are written to a log file in S3 for auditing purposes.

Question: What does S3 offer for in-transit encryption?
Id: 550
Answer: HTTPS, which relies on SSL/TLS

Question: What are the two locations where at-rest encryptions can be performed?
Id: 551
Answer: Client-side encyrption and Server-Side Encryption (SSE)

Question: What 3 forms of Server Side Encryption (SSE) does S3 support?
Id: 552
Answer: S3 managed keys (SSE-S3), S3 Key Management Service (KMS) managed keys (SSE-KMS), Customer managed keys (SSE-C).

Question: What encryption algorithm does AWS SSE use?
Id: 553
Answer: Advanced Encryption Standard AES-256.

Question: How are the keys managed for SSE-S3?
Id: 554
Answer: Each object is encrypted with a unique key chosesn by AWS. The key is encrypted with a master key, which is rotated regularly.

Question: How are the keys managed for SSE-KMS?
Id: 555
Answer: The customer choses the keys and the key policies (e.g. rotation) and stores them securely in AWS using the Key Management Service (KMS).

Question: How are the keys managed for SSE-C?
Id: 556
Answer: The customer must provide the key in each request (only requests over HTTPS are allowed).

Question: Does AWS store the keys when using SSE-C?
Id: 557
Answer: No, Amamzon does not store the keys. For validation purposes it only stores a salt (a hash of the key) from which the key cannot be reconstructed.

SubTopic: Storage Gateway
Id: 558

Question: What service does Storage Gateway provide?
Id: 559
Answer: An on-site virtual appliance that connects on-site storage with AWS storage.

Question: What AWS service provides an on-site virtual appliance that connects on-site storage with AWS storage?
Id: 560
Answer: Storage Gateway.

Question: Which host platforms does Storage Gateway support?
Id: 561
Answer: VMware ESXi, Microsoft Hyper-V (2008 R2 and 2012), Amazon EC2.

Question: Name 4 types of Storage Gateway?
Id: 562
Answer: File gateway, Cached volumes gateway, Stored volumes gateway, Tape gateway (aka VTS gateway)

Question: What does VTS stand for?
Id: 563
Answer: Virtual Tape System.

Question: What does the "Cloud Tiering" use case for Storage Gateway mean?
Id: 564
Answer: Move infrequently used data to multi-tier storage in the cloud to save cost.

Question: What does the "Hybrid Cloud Backup" use case for Storage Gateway mean?
Id: 565
Answer: Store active data in on-prem storage (e.g. NAS or SAN) and automatically make backups which are stored in the cloud.

Question: What does the "Hybrid Cloud Workload" use case for Storage Gateway mean?
Id: 566
Answer: The legacy application can continue to access files using NAS or SAN, while the cloud-native application can use APIs to access S3 or EC2 EBS.

Question: What service does the File gateway provide?
Id: 567
Answer: The File Gateway offers NFS service to local clients, and maps NFS file shares to S3 objects in the AWS cloud.

Question: Where does the File gateway store the files?
Id: 568
Answer: The master copy is stored in S3, and there is a cache on the File gateway for efficiency.

Question: Does the File Gateway transparrently preserve the NFS permissions and attributes?
Id: 569
Answer: Yes, these are stored in S3 metadata.

Question: What storage protocol does the File gateway support?
Id: 570
Answer: Network File System (NFS).

Question: How does the File gateway store files in the cloud?
Id: 571
Answer: As S3 objects.

Question: How does the File gateway integrate with S3?
Id: 572
Answer: S3 features such as lifecycle management, cross-region replication, etc. are available for the S3 objects that represent files.

Question: How does the File gateway integrate with other AWS services?
Id: 573
Answer: Other services, such as Elastic Map Reduce (AMR), can read the S3 objects that represent files.

Question: How does the File gateway enable a migration to cloud-native applications?
Id: 574
Answer: The legacy application can continue to access files using NFS, while the cloud-native application can use APIs to access S3 objects.

Question: Name the 2 kinds of Volume gateway.
Id: 575
Answer: Cached volume gateway and Stored volume gateway.

Question: What storage protocol does a Volume gateway support?
Id: 576
Answer: iSCSI (Internet Small Computer System Interfaca)

Question: Where does the a Volume gateway store the files?
Id: 577
Answer: It periodically stores snapshots as objects in S3.

Question: Name 2 ways in which Volume gateway reduce storage cost in S3.
Id: 578
Answer: The snapshots are incremental and compressed.

Question: How does the Volume gateway integrate with EC2?
Id: 579
Answer: The snapshots stored in S3 can be mounted on virtual machines in EC2 as EBS volumes.

Question: What service does the Cached volume gateway provide?
Id: 580
Answer: Primary data is stored in S3 as snapshots (and presumably also live in EBS), local cache is stored in the on-prem SAN.

Question: What disk sizes does Cached volume gateway support?
Id: 581
Answer: 1 GB - 32 TB.

Question: What service does the Stored volume gateway provide?
Id: 582
Answer: Primary data is locally in the on-prem SAN, periodic snapshots are stored in S3 objects as a backup.

Question: Where does the a Stored volume gateway store the files?
Id: 583
Answer: It periodically stores snapshots as objects in S3.

Question: What disk sizes does Cached volume gateway support?
Id: 584
Answer: 1 GB - 16 TB.

Question: What service does the tape gateway provide?
Id: 585
Answer: The gateway offers a virtual tape device and a virtual media changer device. Tape contents are stored in S3 objects.

Question: Can you continue to use your existing tape backup software (such as NetBackup, Backup Exec, Veeam) with Tape gateway?
Id: 586
Answer: Yes.

Question: Which Storage gateways are used for block-based storage?
Id: 587
Answer: Volume gateway.

Question: How can the storage gateway connect to S3?
Id: 588
Answer: The Internet, Direct Connect, or Virtual Private Cloud (VPC). The latter is used if the gateway is hosted in EC2.

SubTopic: Snowball
Id: 589

Question: What service does Snowball provide?
Id: 590
Answer: Move large amounts of data into or out of the AWS cloud by shipping disks from and to Amazon.

Question: What is the predecessor service for Snowball?
Id: 591
Answer: Import/Export Disk.

Question: What is the main difference between Snowball and Import/Export Disk?
Id: 592
Answer: In Import/Export Disk you provide your own disk devices, whereas with Snowball Amazon provides the device.

Question: Is Import/Export Disk still available?
Id: 593
Answer: Yes, but it is deprecated an no longer advertised on the console.

Question: Name 3 types of Snowball.
Id: 594
Answer: Snowball, Snowball Edge, Snowmobile.

Question: What does a Snowball device look like?
Id: 595
Answer: A ruggedized disk the size of a large suitcase, with an integrated kindle screen and an Ethernet plug.

Question: How do you physically connect a Snowball device to your local storage?
Id: 596
Answer: Using an Ethernet cable (RJ45, SFP+ copper or SFP+ fiber).

Question: What software do you use to transfer content to and from the Snowball device?
Id: 597
Answer: The "snowball" utility that can be downloaded from Amazon is used to copy files to and from the Snowball device.

Question: How are Snowball devices secured?
Id: 598
Answer: Several layers, including: tamper resistent enclosures, 256-bit encryption, TPM module, full erasure after transfer, location tracking.

Question: What is the cost advantage of Snowball relative to sending the data over the Internet?
Id: 599
Answer: Up to 1/5th of the cost.

Question: What is the capacity of a Snowball?
Id: 600
Answer: 80 TB in all regions. 50 TB also availble in US.

Question: How is Snowball Edge different from regular Snowball?
Id: 601
Answer: It also provides compute in addition to storage. It provides 100 TB of storage.

Question: How is Snowmobile different from regular Snowball?
Id: 602
Answer: Snowmobile is container mounted on a truck.

Question: How much capacity to SnowMobile provide?
Id: 603
Answer: Up to 100 Petabyte (= 100,000 Terrabyte = 0.1 Exabyte) of storage.

Question: Where does Snowball store the imported data?
Id: 604
Answer: In S3.

Question: Can Snowball also export data?
Id: 605
Answer: Yes, it can export from S3.

Question: Can Snowball import to or export from Glacier?
Id: 606
Answer: Not directly, you have to go through S3.

Question: How do you get a Snowball device?
Id: 607
Answer: You create a job in the Snowball service console to request a Snowball device.

Question: How does Amazon make sure that the Snowball device was shipped to the right person?
Id: 608
Answer: The downloaded copy utility requires credentials (a manifest file and an unlock code) which are retrieved from the Snowball console.

Question: How does Snowball know in which S3 bucket to store the data?
Id: 609
Answer: You need to specify the bucket when you create the job before the Snowball is shipped and you also need to specify it when you run the copy utility.

SubTopic: Transfer Acceleration
Id: 610

Question: What does S3 Transfer Acceleration do?
Id: 611
Answer: It accelerates uploads to S3 by uploading to a CloudFront Edge Location and then using the optimized Amazon backbone between the Edge Location and the Region.

Question: How do you enable S3 Transfer Acceleration?
Id: 612
Answer: It is a simple Enabled / Disabled option in the bucket properties.

Question: How much of a performance improvement can you expect from S3 Transfer Acceleration?
Id: 613
Answer: If you are close the the S3 region, not much of a difference: 3% improvement or even worse performance. For remote regions up to 40% improvement.

Question: How do I know what the actual improvement will be from my current location to each region?
Id: 614
Answer: Use the "Want to compare your data transfer speed by region?" link in the bucket properties window on the console. It will make actual measurements.

Question: What is the URL for using Transfer Acceleration when uploading a file?
Id: 615
Answer: https://s3-accelerate.amazonaws.com

Question: What is another mechanism than Transfer Acceleration to speed up uploads to S3?
Id: 616
Answer: Multipart upload.

SubTopic: Create a Static Website using S3.
Id: 617

