Question: Who manages the web servers and load balancers when hosting a static website on S3?
Id: 619
Answer: Amazon does.

Question: What types of content cannot be hosted as a static website on S3?
Id: 620
Answer: Anything that is active on the server side: PHP, .net, etc.

Question: Can content that is active on the client side (e.g. JavaScript) be hosted as a static website on S3?
Id: 621
Answer: Yes.

Question: What service do you use to tie a domain name to a static website hosted in S3?
Id: 622
Answer: Route53.

Question: If you tie a domain name to a static website hosted in S3, what must be the name of the S3 bucket?
Id: 623
Answer: The bucket name must be exactly the same as the full domain name (e.g. "example.com")

Question: What is the default URL for a static website hosted in S3 (not using your own domain name)?
Id: 624
Answer: <bucket-name>.s3-website-<region>.amazonaws.com

Question: What permissions should be set for S3 objects that are used as content for a static website on S3?
Id: 625
Answer: Readbable for everyone, i.e. enable public read access.

Question: Name 2 documents to be configured for a bucket that is used to host a static website on S3?
Id: 626
Answer: Index and error.

Question: Give an example of what redirection rules are used for with a static website on S3?
Id: 627
Answer: To redirect example.com (the naked domain name) to www.example.com.

SubTopic: S3 FAQ
Id: 628

Question: How many S3 buckets can you have per account by default?
Id: 629
Answer: 100

Question: Does S3 provide an SLA?
Id: 630
Answer: Yes, and a service credit if the SLA is violated.

Question: Is the cost for S3 the same in all regions?
Id: 631
Answer: No.

Question: Does it cost money to copy S3 data?
Id: 632
Answer: No within a region, yes accross regions.

Question: Does it cost money to transfer data between EC2 and S3?
Id: 633
Answer: No within a region, yes accross regions.

Question: Does it cost money to access S2 data from the console?
Id: 634
Answer: Yes.

Question: Who pays when S3 data is accessed from another account?
Id: 635
Answer: The owner account, unless requester pays is enabled.

Question: What is recommended for uploading very large files to S3?
Id: 636
Answer: Multipart upload.

Question: How much cheaper is the S3 One-Zone-IA storage class than the Standard-IA storage class?
Id: 637
Answer: 20%

Question: How do the S3 Standard, Standard-IA, One-Zone-IA differ in terms of performace?
Id: 638
Answer: They are all similar.

Question: Name 5 types of charges for S3 storage.
Id: 639
Answer: Charges for the amount of storage per month, bandwidth, requests, early delete and small object fees.

Question: What is a key difference between EC2 and S3 One-Zone-IA in terms of how they use AZs?
Id: 640
Answer: EC2 lets you pick the AZ, S3 One-Zone-IA picks the AZ for you.

Topic: Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)
Id: 641

SubTopic: EC2 101
Id: 642

Question: What does EC2 stand for?
Id: 643
Answer: Elastic Compute Cloud.

Question: How does EC2 support scaling up and down?
Id: 644
Answer: By using different instance types (larger and smaller).

Question: How does EC2 support scaling in and out?
Id: 645
Answer: By increasing or decreasing the number of instances.

Question: How does EC2 improve the economic of compute?
Id: 646
Answer: By allowing you to pay only for the capacity that you actually use.

Question: Name the 4 pricing options for EC2 instances.
Id: 647
Answer: On-demand, Reserved, Spot, Dedicated Host.

Question: What is the pricing model for EC2 on-demand instances?
Id: 648
Answer: You pay a fixed price per second or per hour with no commitment.

Question: What is the use case for EC2 on-demand instances?
Id: 649
Answer: No up-front payment or long-term commitment, applications with spiky demands, newly developed applications.

Question: What determines whether you pay per-second or per-hour for EC2 on-demand instances?
Id: 650
Answer: Per-second for Linux and (currently) per-hour for Windows.

Question: What is the pricing model for EC2 reserved instances?
Id: 651
Answer: Provides a capacity reservation for a contractually committed 1 or 3 year term.

Question: What is the use case for EC2 reserved instances?
Id: 652
Answer: Applications with steady and predictable usage, applications that require reserved capacity.

Question: What does the discount of EC2 reserved instances relative to EC2 on-demand instances depend on?
Id: 653
Answer: Term duration (1 or 3 year), how much is paid up-front (all or part), and convertible or not.

Question: How do you achieve maximal savings with EC2 reserved instances?
Id: 654
Answer: 3 year contract, pay everything up-front, non-convertible.

Question: What is a "convertible" EC2 reserved instance?
Id: 655
Answer: The type of EC2 instance can be changed (increased value, not decreased value).

Question: How much can you expect to save by using EC2 reserved instances relative to standard instances?
Id: 656
Answer: Up to 75% for standard up to 54% for convertible.

Question: What is a "scheduled" EC2 reserved instance?
Id: 657
Answer: Reservation is only for certain times and certains days of week or month.

Question: What is the pricing model for EC2 spot instances?
Id: 658
Answer: You big a price, you get the EC2 instance when your bid exceeds the spot price.

Question: What is the use case for EC2 spot instances?
Id: 659
Answer: When you are flexible in terms of when the instance runs. When you require very low cost.

Question: What happens if the spot price for an EC2 instance drops below your bid?
Id: 660
Answer: Your spot instance may be terminated.

Question: If your EC2 spot instance is terminated by AWS because the spot price dropped below your bid, are you charged?
Id: 661
Answer: No, you are not charged for the partial hour in which your spot instance was terminated, not even the part you did use.

Question: If you terminate your EC2 spot instance yourself, are you charged for the partial hour?
Id: 662
Answer: You are charged for the complete hour, even the part of the hour you did not use.

Question: What is the pricing model for EC2 dedicated host instances?
Id: 663
Answer: You pay for a physical server that is reserved for you, upon which EC2 instances are hosted.

Question: Name 2 use cases for EC2 dedicated hosts.
Id: 664
Answer: Licenses bound to the physical server, regulatory requirements.

Question: How are EC2 dedicated hosts purchased?
Id: 665
Answer: On-demand per hour, or reserved for up to 70% off.

Question: In the instance type, what does the letter and digit stand for?
Id: 666
Answer: The letter indicates the speciality (family), the digit the generation.

Question: What is the mnemonic for remembering the EC2 instance types?
Id: 667
Answer: FIGHT Dr Mc PX (Brad Pit Fight Club, Dagobert Duck as a scottish Doctor handing out photos).

Question: What is the speciality of an F family instance type in EC2?
Id: 668
Answer: Field Programmable Gate Array (F for FPGA).

Question: What EC2 instance type provides FPGAs?
Id: 669
Answer: F family.

Question: What are some use cases for F family instance type in EC2?
Id: 670
Answer: Genomics research, financial analytics, real-time video processing, big data, ...

